;There are two categories of data that we collect by default in our release version of Firefox.
Il ha duo categorias de datos que nos normalmente collige in nostre version stabile de Firefox.


;The first is what we call "technical data." This is data about the browser itself, such as the operating system it is running on and information about errors or crashes.
Le prime es le "datos technic": le datos sur le navigator mesme, como le systema de operation usate e informationes sur errores o collapsos.


;The second is what we call "interaction data." This is data about an individual's engagement with Firefox, such as the number of tabs that were open, the status of user preferences, or number of times certain browser features were used, such as screenshots or containers. For example, we collect this data in terms of the back button, that arrow in the upper left corner of your browser that lets you navigate back to a previous webpage in a way that shows us someone used the back button, but doesn’t tell what specific webpages are accessed.
Le secunde es le "datos de interaction": le datos de uso personal de Firefox, como le numero de schedas aperte, le stato del preferentias del usator, o le numero de vices que certe functiones del navigator ha essite usate, p.ex. instantaneos de schermo o schedas contextual. Per exemplo, nos collige tal datos sur le uso del button Retro, le flecha in le angulo superior sinistre de tu navigator que te permitte retornar a un previe pagina web, de un maniera que nos informa que alcuno ha usate le button Retro, ma non qual paginas web specific ha essite visitate.


;Do you collect more data in pre-release versions of Firefox?
Collige vos plus datos in le versiones preliminar de Firefox?


;Sort-of. In addition to the data described above, we receive crash and error reports by default in pre-release version of Firefox.
Plus o minus. In addition al datos describite supra, nos normalmente recipe reportos de collapso e errores del versiones preliminar de Firefox.


